Thus the tragedy of their splitting up, as they have the same problems of loneliness but their trauma gets in the way.  It’s such a great surprise when they get back together, too, and are able to complete each other.

As an H-doujin, the fetishes of filling and impregnation align really well with the themes of breaking loneliness and isolation. We can understand that Tenryuu’s response to being creampied is not just sexual but also because it breaks down her emotional walls for a second, which makes her excellently rendered reactions feel earned. Meanwhile Supply Depot’s battle against her libido is also her internal battle between wanting to claim Tenryuu as hers and fearing her abandonment even after that intimacy. Finally, the promise of impregnation, something to tie them together and unify their lonely souls, is a microcosm of their relationship; they both desperately want it, but are afraid of it too, and that drives the sexual tension.

(3/3)

As Tenryuu falls for her, though, she tries to break her out of her shell, to tease and flirt with her, and Supply Depot’s control slips and she ravishes Tenryuu, which is of course also bangin’.

Tenryuu tries to fill Supply Depot’s loneliness, but realizing how much she’s come to care about Tenryuu terrifies Supply Depot because she’s certain the other girl will leave, and she pushes her away. That last main sex scene speaks for itself; it’s super tragic and self-sacrificing, and they never reach any kind of completion, but they’re both sexually and emotionally raw, and try to get as much of each other as they can without Tenryuu taking responsibility for her desires or Supply Depot hurting her or accepting her as a part of her life. Both are being as honest as they can—Tenryuu with her desire, Supply Depot with her brutality—but they don’t confront their trauma. Tenryuu doesn’t ask to stay so she won’t be rejected, and Supply Depot avoids getting close or asking her to stay. (2/3)

Like actually, gotta comment again. Not only is it obviously super hot, but it’s meaningfully hot. Tenryuu was thrown away for being weak so she’s looking down on Supply Depot in the beginning because she’s insecure and projecting, and repressing her desire to connect physically and emotionally through that. She’s deeply lonely and has really good chemistry with Supply Depot, and the strength of the passions she’s trying to repress overcome her willpower, which is of course hot as fuck.

Meanwhile, Supply Depot also has a ton of abandonment issues, and doesn’t want to get serious or fully engage with Tenryuu because she thinks she’ll leave—which is really valid, given how flippantly and manipulatively Tenryuu treats her to begin with. (1/3)
